25|$|In 1959, Schell {{acted in}} the role of <b>a</b> <b>defense</b> <b>attorney</b> on a live TV {{production}} of Judgment at Nuremberg, a fictionalized re-creation of the Nuremberg War Trials, in an edition of Playhouse 90. His performance in the TV drama was considered so good that he and Werner Klemperer were the only members of the original cast selected to play the same parts in the 1961 film version. He won the Academy Award for Best Actor, which was the first win for a German-speaking actor since World War II.|$|E
25|$|Under English law {{effective}} {{during the}} {{ratification of the}} U.S. Constitution, including the Treason Act 1351, there were essentially five species of treason. Of the five, the Constitution adopted only two: levying war and adhering to enemies. Omitted were species of treason involving encompassing (or imagining) {{the death of the}} king, certain types of counterfeiting, and finally fornication with women in the royal family of the sort which could call into question the parentage of royal successors. James Wilson wrote the original draft of this section, and he was involved as <b>a</b> <b>defense</b> <b>attorney</b> for some accused of treason against the Patriot cause.|$|E
25|$|Veteran CCPD detective Paul Rivera led {{the murder}} investigation. Originally, an unnamed man {{was hired to}} defend Saldívar but withdrew from the case on April 4 fearing {{community}} retaliation, and concerned about his children's reaction when they learned he was defending Saldívar whom they disliked. Judge Mike Westergren began searching for <b>a</b> <b>defense</b> <b>attorney.</b> Prosecutor Carlos Valdez was designated lead prosecutor, while Mark Skurka was appointed his legal counsel. On April 6, a grand jury was called to determine whether to indict Saldívar for murder. After about an hour, the jury had returned a true bill and the indictment was randomly assigned to the 214th District Court. Carlos Valdez believed that a speedy trial with Westergren presiding over the case was probable.|$|E
